We picked up a Ryobi E49CM01 Power Meter and plugged it into the back of our Thing-O-Matic (MK7), recording data under various conditions. Next step will be to crack the device open and attempt some direct logging as opposed to the otherwise tried and true "Look and Type" method. Here are some highlights: Idle: 10 Watts
Enable Button from RepG Control Panel: 44.75 Watts
Maintain 100C on Print Bed: 41.75 additional Watts above Idle
Maintain 220C on MK7: 46.5 additional Watts above Idle
During a Print (MK7 = 220C, Bed = 100C): 107.75 Watts
Cost of 8hr Print @ 7 cents per kwh: $0.06 All our data is included here but I would really encourage going here: http://www.protoparadigm.com/2011/10/makerbot-thing-o-matic-power-consumption/ and reading a short write up that can give a better presentation of the data. We should have similar numbers for the Ultimaker and Mosaic shortly.

Naturally, there are many factors that affect your actual power use as well as your ability to accurately track that consumption. We'll be tracking down ways to more accurately predict how much power your printer is consuming but this should provide a decent starting place. And of course, throw any questions and observations in the comments.

title: Double Sided Spool Holder for Original Prusa i3

description.text: This is my first, simple modification to my Original Prusa i3 printer (which is awesome by the way). This printer is capable of colour printing by changing filament during a print however I wasn't happy with changing spools over in case I knocked the print bed or similar. So I created the double sided spool holder (which sits between two spools) allowing me to have more than one spool mounted allowing for easy filament changeover and (hopefully) less chance of bumbling knocks. This was adapted from the original print part STL files kindly supplied by Prusa Research. I don't believe the files have been uploaded as a 'thing' so I can't really say it's a remix - even though it is. I looked in to printing the 'dowel' piece as a perfect cylinder but I read that I might have issues with parts fitting so I went for an octagon that allows for an easier press fit. Thanks to Make for the tips (http://makezine.com/2015/07/22/tips-3d-printing-press-fit-parts/). I believe Karlosek's Spool Hole Reduction thing (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:938464) will work with the octagon dowel as it is the same diameter as the original cylindrical part. I think I've babbled on long enough so I'll leave you to print this - if you want to obviously. Any feedback, good or bad, is appreciated.

I'm not sure what make of extractor hood it is, but you should be able to recognize the original clips from the image showing the broken clip. The clips are required to lock the underside of the hood (where the grease filter is located) in place. There are 2 clips, one on each side of the under hood cover. I wanted to make my own balancer for planes with ruller.
Ruller will allow to measure distance of CoG in mm from leading or trailing edge of wing. No need to mark it on wing bottom and balance plane on fingers. Size of vertical part of leg is 10x10 mm. So, center (balance point) is 5 mm from front/rear side. Scale on ruller started from 0 (leading edge), you should deduct 5 mm from required distance and this length should be between vertical part of ruller and side of leg. Example: you need 33 mm from leading edge to CoG, ruller should meet leg on 28 mm mark. Balancer could be easily disassemled for storage or travel to flight site for example.
Photos shows assembled and disassembled balancer. NB: You will need to print two legs, they are identical. Horizontal clearance (fuselage width) - 130 mm
Vertical clearance (from wing bottom to bottom of fuselage - 93 mm. Please comment it and if you need bigger balancer just let me know.

So these little guys are the creatures of thingiverse. Then come my desire to create a customizable creatures that can become as diverse as its users want. So this will be an ongoing project of adding more pieces to create all different types critters. So I am hoping to get lots of people involved in adding parts to their collection or give them accessories and decals. So, give them a lives and stories of their own to tell. Designing to me is very much about sharing and feeding off other people. I just wanted to do something very community based and get myself to model something for myself and others as often as possible I am going to try to add a new piece ever 2 days or so. This is the first iteration. So fellow members if you want them bigger (there around 2in x 3in x 2in) let me know and let me know about how much detail I can model in. I was debating one with scales but didn't want to cause hardship when they didn't show up well in a print due to size same goes for hole tolerance.
Also if more joints and moving parts are wanted I might do a ball joint version. I will need testers for this undertaking.. I will take piece requests too. So if you want a crazy tail or something or another body type drop me a line it will keep me creating. So print the pieces and create your own creature give him or her a name . Make them in different colors. Paint them decal them. And show them off. Try making some glow in the dark with a black marker design. It really up to you. There here for the fun of it.. There a desk toy you can point at and say I made that or an army of little minions to do your making bidding. Anyway that is if for now feel free to ask question. Create a story or world for them. Make an animation out of them physical or digital. It all about open source do what you want with them. Just put it up so everyone can see and feed off it!

So Instructions... Pretty much print and clean up and decorate how you see fit and plug the pieces that make your creature yours in place. I currently have 3 different tails, 3 types of ears and 3 types of mouths for this 1 head type and 1 body type and some hair you will need to glue the hair. I will be adding head types and body types and other pieces to it in the future and encourage other to add to it too.
If you want it to look like a cool resin like art toy some sanding will be needed so you can add cool design on a smooth surface. So the disclaimer I am 3d printer less at home so I haven't been able to print them so if there are any issues let me know. I am use to dealing polyjet and zcorps for work but I can't sneak these in with work prints... They stand out to much and I dont think my boss would like to be billed for them..hehe. But I have checked the meshes and they come up at solid and such so hopeful no issues. They are currently tight fits for the pieces if you need this adjusted let me know I included a step for people as most software can take a step (check your import settings). Also I have eye decals if you print these on a white sticker sheet and cut them out you can have eyes for your creature. I will add more when I am more in an illustration mood. You can get them to be more eye like by coating the top with some clear nail varnish. That's all for now. If you print them and have time feel free to add to the instructions. Also show off your print and process! UPDATE: New Step file has been added where parts are orientated flat and apart for your printing need. If I need to add supports some tips will be need. Update: Zip of all parts today now uploaded. Update: 10/26/11 Upload and update on the body as it seem the tail hole was missing.. (very sorry) Also new tail. Any luck with prints or do I need simplify that characters more? Update 11/20/11 New ears: ears4.stl Cheers!! Happy Making!

title: Parametric helical Darrieus vertical axis wind turbine

description.text:
Get the new version here!
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15083 I am currently in the middle of my Repstrap build, and my brother-in-law asked me why I am investing so much energy to get this done, if I can redirect my efforts into some way to obtain renewable energy (in order to get away from the high electricity bills) This is my answer to him! Thanks again to buzz for his Parametric NACA airfoil code.
This project is dependent on the Parametric NACA4 Library I posted earlier.

1) Print the parts required: You will need one top and one base, and as many add-on sections as you require. To make it a constant torque turbine, I would recommend printing two add-on sections, as in the image included, or (2+3n) pieces.
2) The holes through the blades are continuous, so it might be possible to thread wire rope or printing filament through the blades to reinforce and attach the sections together without only relying on glue
3) the central section is also parametric, and defaults to 8mm, allowing you to use M8 threaded bolt for the drive shaft to the generator. Since the shaft mount and motor/generator mount will depend on the type used, I will leave the design of that section as an exercise to the user.
When/if I have my printer running, I will probably publish the motor enclosure, using a commonly available motor/generator as the basis. And don't forget - It's Parametric! Print it as large as you dare. Play with the settings, including the radius and NACA profile. I suspect I will print quite a couple of these variants when my printer gets on line... Something else to try may be to only print the add-on modules in multiples of three in order to get the build size up on printers with smaller build envelopes. As is the STL files attached are more likely POC model sized than for generating any serious power. Then again, there is merit in having a couple of long thin spires combined rather than one big turbine...
